"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780309","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-13","<p>Prior to 2013/14 the Government provided the BBC World Service with Grant-in-Aid funding through the Foreign and ​​Commonwealth Office. From 2014/15 onwards core World Service activity was funded through the Licence Fee. In 2015 the Government announced additional funding for the World Service for the BBC World 2020 programme. £291 million will be invested from 2016/17 to 2019/20 to expand provision, including the creation of 12 new language services. New and enhanced services for BBC World Service will provide more people around the world with access to accurate, impartial and independent information.</p><p>The published BBC figures for government funding to the World Service, including Grant-in-Aid prior to 2014/15 and BBC World 2020 funding from 2016/17, are therefore as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>£m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>265.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>268.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>265.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>255.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>244.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>238.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>34.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>85.0</p></td></tr></tbody></table>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-11-13T17:44:50.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780309/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780309/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780309/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-30","BBC World Service: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much the BBC World Service received in government subsidy in each of the last ten years.","false","Biography information for Lord Dobbs",,"Lord Dobbs","HL2673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780310","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-13","<p>The British Council has provided the following figures from their Annual Reports which reflect the total resources expended for each of the last ten years.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total resources expended (£'000)</p></td><td><p>557,402</p></td><td><p>621,579</p></td><td><p>708,083</p></td><td><p>665,321</p></td><td><p>720,413</p></td><td><p>785,333</p></td><td><p>880,410</p></td><td><p>975,880</p></td><td><p>971,363</p></td><td><p>1,085,934</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Further information on the British Council’s finances are available from their Annual Reports which are online and in the parliamentary library. ​</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-11-13T17:45:14.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780310/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780310/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780310/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-30","British Council: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what was the operational budget for the British Council in each of the last ten years.","false","Biography information for Lord Dobbs",,"Lord Dobbs","HL2674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780311","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-13","<p>The Government keeps all taxes under review. Decisions on taxation are a matter for the Chancellor and are considered as part of the Budget process.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-11-13T15:47:55.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780311/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780311/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780311/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-30","Insurance Premium Tax","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they plan to review the level of insurance premium tax.","false","Biography information for Baroness Golding",,"Baroness Golding","HL2675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780312","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is responsible for monitoring and regulating the insurance industry. They set the conduct standards required of insurance firms, which aims to ensure consumers are treated fairly and have fair access to affordable insurance products.</p><p> </p><p>If it becomes clear that intervention is necessary, the FCA is able to do so. For example, in April 2017 the FCA took action on the practice of insurers increasing premiums at renewal.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2677","2017-11-06T16:04:43.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780312/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780312/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780312/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-30","House Insurance: Fees and Charges","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of whether insurance premiums levels have deterred people from taking out insurance on their homes.","false","Biography information for Baroness Golding",,"Baroness Golding","HL2676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780313","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is responsible for monitoring and regulating the insurance industry. They set the conduct standards required of insurance firms, which aims to ensure consumers are treated fairly and have fair access to affordable insurance products.</p><p> </p><p>If it becomes clear that intervention is necessary, the FCA is able to do so. For example, in April 2017 the FCA took action on the practice of insurers increasing premiums at renewal.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2676","2017-11-06T16:04:43.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780313/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780313/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780313/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-30","Insurance: Business","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of how insurance premiums have affected how businesses have determined their investment plans.","false","Biography information for Baroness Golding",,"Baroness Golding","HL2677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780314","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-13","<p>Such an assessment has not been made. If the policy has the anticipated effect of encouraging young people to remain in the parental home we would expect a positive impact on employment levels. The fact that such claimants receive a lower level of benefit results in them moving free of the Universal Credit earning taper at a lower level of wages. From that point they keep 100 per cent rather than 37 per cent of every additional £1 they earn, which provides a strong work incentive.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2017-11-13T14:07:50.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780314/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780314/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780314/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-30","Universal Credit: Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the financial effect resulting from the Universal Credit (Housing Costs Element for claimants aged 18 to 21) (Amendment) Regulations 2017 on youth employment figures.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780315","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-13","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not have a role in specifically approving business models used by NHS Trusts and Foundation Trusts. It is HMRC’s role to collect the taxes that are legally due, including VAT.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-11-13T15:53:07.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780315/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780315/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780315/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-30","NHS: VAT","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many approvals have been given to financial models that allow wholly owned subsidiaries of NHS Trusts and Foundation Trusts providing services to the NHS Trust or Foundation Trust that owns them to be established in order to claim VAT refunds.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780316","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-13","<p>Workforce planning is primarily the responsibility of each department to determine based on their individual operational and policy requirements. Each department has their own spending agreements with HM Treasury and are responsible for ensuring they have the right workforce and capability in place to deliver their commitments.</p><p>We are consolidating our estate in central London and, since 2010, have reduced the number of offices from 185 to 54. The Public Bodies Relocation Programme seeks to move significant numbers of civil servants and other public servants out of London. This is part of the Government's Industrial Strategy and seeks to help rebalance the UK economy.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-11-13T13:52:30.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780316/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780316/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780316/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-30","Civil Servants: Midlands","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to re-locate civil servants from London to (1) Birmingham, (2) the West Midlands, and (3) the Midlands as defined in the Midlands Engine Strategy.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780317","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-13","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply and I will place a copy of their letter in the Library of the House.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-11-13T13:55:59.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780317/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780317/answer","HL 2681 Lord Hunt.pdf","HL 2681 Lord Hunt.pdf","UKSA Response ","UKSA Response ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780317/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-30","Civil Servants: Location","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many civil servants employed by HM Government had their primary place of work in (1) England, broken down by region, (2) Scotland, (3) Wales, and (4) Northern Ireland, in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780318","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-13","Successive governments have aimed to keep the cost to businesses of VAT administration to the minimum necessary for HM Revenue and Customs to risk assess and assure tax receipts. HMRC routinely receives and maintains the information supplied on the 9 box return of a business, but not detailed information in respect of their suppliers and customers. However, businesses must retain for six years business records with that level of detail, and make these available for inspection.",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-11-13T15:48:23.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780318/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780318/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780318/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-30","NHS: VAT","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Mel Stride MP on 12 September (HC8140), why HMRC does not hold information on VAT revenues from NHS bodies at a sufficient level of detail that it would enable them to calculate how much revenue is lost as a result of NHS organisations setting up subsidiary companies with the purpose of reducing their VAT payments.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780319","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-13","<p>Any need for an advance payment or other financial or budgeting support is established at the outset of a claim for Universal Credit. In the initial new claim interview, work coaches are trained to offer personal budgeting support and assess whether claimants need help to manage until their first Universal Credit payment. We have taken steps to increase awareness of this support by amending guidance to ensure that claimants are aware at the start of their claim of the maximum amount they can receive and repayment period as an advance.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2017-11-13T14:57:43.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780319/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780319/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780319/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-30","Universal Credit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government by what methods they make it generally known that Universal Credit applicants can ask for 50 per cent advances, or other forms of emergency assistance, when faced with serious cash problems.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780320","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>This Government is committed to protecting the most vulnerable by ensuring that the welfare system provides a strong safety-net for those who need it. That is why it continues to spend over £90 billion a year on welfare for people of working age. The decision on engagement with food banks and other local community initiatives will continue to remain at local discretion: where Jobcentre Plus is invited to work with a food bank provider and where there is local need.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2017-11-06T17:07:57.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780320/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780320/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780320/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-30","Food Poverty","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have made an assessment of the Feeding Birkenhead project; if so, what lessons they have learnt about preventing destitution; and what steps they are taking to apply those lessons.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780321","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Government has engaged with Trussell Trust as a key stakeholder but not specifically on the subject of food and fuel poverty in England and Wales.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2017-11-06T17:08:21.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780321/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780321/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780321/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-30","Poverty","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions they have had with the Trussell Trust about food and fuel poverty in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780322","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-10","<p>Lebanon has shown enormous generosity in hosting around 1.5 million Syrian refugees – the highest concentrations per capita anywhere in the world. Building the resilience of the regional countries affected by the Syrian crisis has been<strong>,</strong> and continues to be<strong>,</strong> a top priority for the UK. The UK has led the international community in mobilising support for Syrian refugees, including by co-hosting pledging conferences in London (2016) and Brussels (2017). The UK has provided £466 million to support Syrian refugees in Lebanon and the Lebanese host communities. We remain at the forefront of delivering on pledges, having already allocated 97% of money pledged for 2017.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-11-10T12:36:57.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780322/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780322/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780322/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-30","Lebanon: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, in the light of the UN High Commissioner for Refugees figures showing that Lebanon is the country with the highest per capita concentration of refugees worldwide, what priority they give to providing refugee aid to Lebanon.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780323","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-13","<p>Our Consul General in Jerusalem is in regular discussion with the Palestinian Authority (PA) ​about the process of reconciliation, making clear our support for the PA resuming government functions in Gaza and underlining the need for any future Palestinian unity Government to comply with the Quartet Principles: to renounce violence, recognise Israel and accept previously signed agreements.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-11-13T17:46:57.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780323/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780323/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780323/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-30","Palestinians: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what means they are employing to support and make effective the newly agreed Palestinian Government of National Unity.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780324","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-13","<p>We do not have payment timeliness data broken down to the characteristics being requested. The latest data, published on 2 October on gov.uk, provides the most up to date information on payment timeliness and methodology, and is attached.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2017-11-13T15:24:12.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780324/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780324/answer","HL2688 universal-credit-payment-timeliness-statistical-ad-hoc.pdf","HL2688 universal-credit-payment-timeliness-statistical-ad-hoc.pdf","Universal Credit Payment Timeliness Data","Universal Credit Payment Timeliness Data","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780324/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-30","Universal Credit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, what was the (1) shortest, (2), median, and (3) longest, delay in days in paying Universal Credit, in each of the last four quarters of the financial year for which figures are available; whether those figures are based on all Universal Credit payments or payments to a representative group of applicants; and if the latter, what was the size of that group, and how was it composed.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780325","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Department for Transport’s data on road accidents collected from police STATS19 returns reporting personal injury road collisions does not collect definitive information about whether any of the road users involved in a collision were breaking the law.</p><p> </p><p>There is information in the STATS19 database to indicate, in the opinion of the police officer attending the scene, what contributory factors might have played a part in a particular road collision. However, this information is not recorded for all collisions and is based on the officer’s initial opinion assessment only before any legal action has taken place. In addition, information about breath test results at the scene is collected but there is no record of whether this led to a prosecution or conviction.</p><p><br>Data on prosecutions are collected by the Ministry of Justice.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2017-11-08T13:07:55.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780325/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780325/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780325/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-30","Roads: Accidents","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what data are collected on the number of people killed and injured by road users who are breaking the law; and who collects those data.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL2689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780326","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-13","<p>The Prime Minister, the Foreign Secretary and I raised all our dual national consular cases, including Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe's, with our Iranian counterparts in the margins of the United Nations General Assembly in September. Last month, the Foreign Secretary once again discussed the importance of these cases with Foreign Minister Zarif and Vice President Salehi, as did the Minister of State for the Middle East in a phone call with the Iranian Ambassador to the UK. Our Ambassador in Tehran also raises these cases at every opportunity.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-11-13T17:45:58.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780326/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780326/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780326/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-30","Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what recent actions they have taken to help secure the release of Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe from detention in Iran.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL2690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780327","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-13","<p>The Prime Minister, the Foreign Secretary and I raised all our dual national consular cases, including Mr Kamal Foroughi's, with our Iranian counterparts in the margins of the United Nations General Assembly in September. Last month, the Foreign Secretary once again discussed the importance of these cases with Foreign Minister Zarif and Vice President Salehi, as did the Minister of State for the Middle East in a phone call with the Iranian Ambassador to the UK. Our Ambassador in Tehran also raises these cases at every opportunity.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-11-13T17:41:49.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780327/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780327/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780327/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-30","Kamal Foroughi","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what recent actions they have taken to help secure the release of Kamal Foroughi from detention in Iran.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL2691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780328","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-13","<p>The UK Government has engaged at Ministerial and official levels to urge the Government of the Maldives to reverse its decision to lift its de facto moratorium on the death penalty.</p><p>The Foreign Secretary wrote to the President of the Maldives on this matter on 29 August, as did my colleague the Minister for Asia and the Pacific on 31 August. The former Minister for Asia and the Pacific, Alok Sharma MP, also raised this issue with the Maldivian Minister for Foreign Affairs when they met at the UN Human Rights Council in February. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office 2016 Human Rights and Democracy report highlighted our concerns, including upholding death sentences against minors.</p><p>We have consistently made clear our opposition to the death penalty in all circumstances as a matter of principle. It is a violent and ineffective form of punishment that has no deterrent or protective value​.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-11-13T17:42:23.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780328/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780328/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780328/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-30","Maldives: Capital Punishment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations, if any, they have made to the authorities in the Maldives not to resume use of the death penalty.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL2692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780329","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-10","<p>Table 5 of the Monthly Statistics of Building Materials and Components published by the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy shows that in 2016 there were 50,153,000 tonnes of sand and gravel sold in England and Wales, of which 11,770,000 tonnes were marine dredged – which is equivalent to 23%.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2017-11-10T12:48:47.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780329/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780329/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780329/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-30","Aggregates: Seas and Oceans","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their estimate of the amount that marine aggregates contribute to the sand and gravel requirements of England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL2693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780330","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-13","<p>In the English marine area dredging to extract aggregates, including sand, gravel, and other marine minerals, from the seabed requires a licence from the Marine Management Organisation (MMO).</p><p>The MMO scrutinises every application to ensure that no unacceptable impacts will arise as a result of any permitted aggregate dredging operations. All applications must, therefore, contain sufficient data on which to base an informed decision. A number of assessments, including an Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) and Coastal Impact Study (CIS), are undertaken to support aggregate dredging applications. The CIS assumes a “worst case scenario” and includes information on wave modelling, sediment transport and an assessment of the possibility of adverse effects on the coastline.</p><p>Should a licence be granted, the site will also be subject to a programme of monitoring throughout the duration of the licence, in order to validate conclusions from EIA and CIS. Should any unacceptable environmental impacts be identified during monitoring, the licence can be varied, suspended or revoked.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-11-13T12:09:14.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780330/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780330/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780330/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-30","Minerals: Coastal Areas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the strength of environmental considerations when considering the further development of coastal mineral extraction.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL2694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780331","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-13","<p>We do not collect this data as there is no domestic or EU legislation that obliges it and we do not want to burden business with unnecessary reporting requirements.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-11-13T12:07:32.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780331/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780331/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780331/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-30","Aggregates: Recycling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their estimate of the amount of recycled products used in aggregates produced in the UK.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL2695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780332","Home Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Home Office has been working closely with the Employers’ Initiative to encourage employers to take further action to support victims of domestic abuse in the workplace. This includes engaging with other departments and non-departmental bodies to raise awareness of the Employers’ Initiative and working with wider partners to ensure employers have the guidance and tools to offer high-quality support to victims.</p><p>The Home Office will be represented at the conference on the 29 November.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL2697 ; HL2698","2017-11-07T16:47:56.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780332/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780332/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780332/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-30","Domestic Abuse: Employment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to encourage departments and non-departmental bodies to engage with, and support, the Employers' Initiative on Domestic Abuse; and what progress has been made to date.","false","Biography information for Lord McColl of Dulwich",,"Lord McColl of Dulwich","HL2696"
