"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780673","Department for International Trade","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) headcount has grown to more than 3,590, which includes an international network of more than 1,300 people. DIT headcount has grown by 43% since July 2016 (an increase of 1,087 from 2,504 to 3,591.</p><p>The turnover rate for civil servants in DIT for the 12 month period from October 2016 to September 2017 was 11.8%.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-11-09T11:39:15.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780673/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780673/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780673/answer",,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-30","Department for International Trade: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what proportion of civil service posts in his Department was vacant for a week or longer since his Department was established; and what the turnover rate for civil servants in his Department has been in that period.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780674","Department for International Trade","false","2017-11-07","<p>All World Trade Organisation Members have at least one preferential trade agreement in place. As set out in the Department for International Trade’s 9 October policy paper, <em>Preparing for our future UK trade policy </em>(<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/preparing-for-our-future-uk-trade-policy" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/preparing-for-our-future-uk-trade-policy</a>), the Government will seek to transition all existing EU trade agreements and other EU preferential arrangements, as we prepare to leave the EU.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-11-07T16:34:42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780674/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780674/answer",,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-30","World Trade Organisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate he has made on the number of countries which solely rely on World Trade Organisation schedules.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","110259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780675","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Treasury has committed over £250 million of additional spending in 2017-18 to prepare for EU Exit from the Reserve. Departmental allocations will be set out at Supplementary Estimates in the usual way. This is in addition to the £412m of additional funding over the parliament announced at Autumn Statement 2016 for the Department of International Trade, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and the Department for Exiting the European Union. That means the government has allocated over half a billion pounds so far in funding to ensure a successful exit from the EU.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-11-07T13:51:14.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780675/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780675/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780675/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-30","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what information his Department holds on the cost to the public purse of each Department's workstreams on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","110257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780676","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-02","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union and the Department for Communities and Local Government are working closely with stakeholders and regional partners across the country, including elected mayors in the North West, to understand issues related to exit and identify any regional implications. The Government will continue to champion devolution to local government and is committed to devolving greater powers to local government where there is economic rationale to do so.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-11-02T17:16:25.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780676/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780676/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780676/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-30","Local Government: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions his Department has had with council leaders and mayors in the North West on potential new powers for local authorities when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","110296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780677","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-07","<p>Stakeholder engagement is a central element of our ongoing plan to negotiate a successful outcome and achieve the best deal for the UK and the EU. We are committed to hearing from as many organisations, companies and institutions as possible, including trade unions.</p><p>One of the Secretary of State’s first meetings following the Department’s creation was with the General Secretary of the Trades Union Congress. The Secretary of State for the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial also meets the Trades Union Congress regularly.</p><p>Details of Ministerial meetings are published in the Department’s Quarterly Transparency Returns, which are made publicly available on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a>.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-11-07T16:06:37.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780677/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780677/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780677/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-30","Department for Exiting the European Union: Trade Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many meetings he has had with trades unions since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","110201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780678","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union has not had any meetings with Simon Stevens, the Chief Executive of NHS England, since July 2016. However, the Secretary of State for Health has regular meetings with Mr Stevens on a range of topics, including on preparations for the UK’s Exit from the EU, and Department of Health (DH) officials are working closely with NHS England to prepare for EU exit.</p><p>The Department for Exiting the European Union works closely with every department, including DH, to build a detailed understanding of how withdrawal will affect domestic policies and to ensure preparations are being made across government both for a negotiated settlement and for the unlikely scenario in which no mutually satisfactory agreement can be reached.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-11-07T15:49:55.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780678/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780678/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780678/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-30","NHS England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many meetings he has had with the chief executive of NHS England since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","110202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780679","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-13","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union does not centrally hold information on vacancies week by week. The Department undertakes regular resource reviews to ensure that we are appropriately resourced to deal with the task at hand.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Since the creation of DExEU, 165 individuals have left the Department. The Department has adopted a flexible and adaptable resourcing model and a significant proportion of this total represents the contractual exit of agency workers, secondees, contractors and fast streamers. The figure also includes a number of planned departures during the Department’s life; including a significant number of individuals who were on short term loan from other Government Departments brought in to aid in the establishment of DExEU.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is recruiting the brightest and the best from across the civil service, the wider public sector and the private sector. The Department now has over 550 staff, and is growing fast.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-11-13T15:47:14.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780679/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780679/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780679/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-30","Department for Exiting the European Union: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what proportion of civil service posts in his Department was vacant for a week or longer since his Department was established; and what the turnover rate for civil servants in his Department has been in that period.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780680","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-07","<p>We are committed to securing a deal that works for the entire United Kingdom, including Northern Ireland. We have been clear from the start that the devolved administrations should be fully engaged in this process. For the future partnership paper on security, law enforcement and criminal justice, both the Department for Exiting the European Union and the Home Office have engaged at an official level with the Northern Ireland Civil Service, in the absence of a Northern Ireland Executive.</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to positive and productive engagement with the devolved administrations, including a restored Northern Ireland Executive, as we take forward this important work. We are also determined to hear from as many organisations, companies and institutions as possible to build a national consensus around our negotiating position.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-11-07T17:02:08.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780680/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780680/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/780680/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-30","Security: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what plans he has to consult (a) the PSNI, (b) the Northern Ireland Department of Justice and (c) other bodies in Northern Ireland on the proposals contained in his Department's future partnership paper on security, law enforcement and criminal justice, published on 18 September 2017.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","110377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/781356","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-02","<p>The Government is fully committed to negotiating a deep and special partnership with the European Union and negotiations are progressing well. However, as a responsible government, we are ensuring plans are in place for a range of outcomes, including the unlikely scenario where the UK leaves the EU without a deal. <br><br>The Department for Exiting the European Union is working alongside each Government department to build a clear understanding of how withdrawing from the EU will affect its existing policies and services. Plans are well developed and have been designed to provide the flexibility to respond to a number of potential outcomes.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-11-02T13:01:37.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/781356/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/781356/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/781356/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-30","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether his Department is helping to prepare contingency plans across Government in the event of a no deal outcome from the negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Eddie Hughes","Walsall North","Eddie Hughes","901553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778724","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>​The Government opposes extremism in all its forms. We believe in the fundamental values of liberty, democracy and respect for human rights and we continue to work internationally to uphold those values.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-11-07T17:47:45.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778724/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778724/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-27","Europe: Radicalism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the implications of the success of extremist parties in recent European elections for the stability of the EU and the Council of Europe, especially in respect of the maintenance of human rights.","false","Biography information for Baroness Deech",,"Baroness Deech","HL2633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778725","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-10","<p>The Minister for Asia and the Pacific will be replying shortly to the letter from the Royal Hong Kong Police Association which was received on 16 October.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-11-10T14:47:03.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778725/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778725/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-27","Hong Kong: Police","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 25 October (HL1889), what was their response to the letter from the Royal Hong Kong Police Association to the Minister of State for the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, Mark Field MP, dated 16 October.","false","Biography information for Lord Goodlad",,"Lord Goodlad","HL2634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778726","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2017-11-14","<p>As Parliamentary Under Secretary Robin Walker said in his opening remarks to the House on 1st November, the Government has not produced a series of sectoral impact assessments. The Government has produced a wide mix of qualitative and quantitative analysis, contained in a range of documents developed at different times since the referendum. It is constantly evolving and being updated based on our discussions with industry and our negotiations with the EU, but it is not, and nor has it ever been, a series of impact assessments examining the quantitative impact of Brexit on these sectors. The Secretary of State has said that he will provide sector analysis to the Exiting the European Union Committee in an informative and accessible way as soon as is possible.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-11-14T17:43:50.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778726/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778726/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2017-10-27","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government (1) which (a) departments, and (b) ministers, received the sector-by-sector Brexit impact assessment analysis papers; and (2) which ministers received a specific analysis (and which one) and which ministers received a complete set.","false","Biography information for Baroness Goudie",,"Baroness Goudie","HL2635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778727","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID) II implements commitments made by the G20 in 2009 in light of the financial crisis. The UK achieved its key objectives in negotiations, and the government considers that MiFID II will strengthen investor protection and the transparency of financial markets. The government fully recognises the extensive impact that MiFID II will have on the financial services industry.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-11-06T16:04:07.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778727/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778727/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-27","Financial Markets: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their assessment of the Markets in Financial Instruments Directive, or "Mifid II" rules.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL2636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778728","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-07","<p>Collaboration is a powerful way for groups of farmers to share knowledge and expertise, market information and good farming practice, exercise joint purchasing power and strengthen their negotiating position within the supply chain.</p><p> </p><p>As we leave the EU, we have the opportunity to explore how we can encourage greater levels of producer collaboration, including through co-operatives. Ministers and officials have discussed this with Co-operatives UK, the business network for UK co-operatives, and other industry stakeholders on several occasions.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-11-07T15:45:42.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778728/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778728/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-27","Agriculture: Cooperatives","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what action they are taking to support the growth of co-operatives in the agricultural sector.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL2637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778729","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-02","<p>Co-operatives, ranging from small businesses to nationally recognised names such as John Lewis, play a valuable role in the UK with nearly 7,000 independent co-operatives contributing more than £36 billion to the British economy. Employing 226,000 people, the co-operative sector employs 0.7% of the UK’s workforce, making it a significant player in the economy. Co-operative UK published a report in 2017 which recorded 249 co-operatives engaged in the energy and environment sector, with a turnover of £12.7m.</p><p>The Government funded the Community Shares programme over 2012- 2018 enabling growth of the market and seeing over £120m raised by communities to buy-out and run local enterprises which included the development of new community energy schemes.</p><p>Co-operatives continue to play an important role in local and community energy projects, in particular. This Government is committed to empowering communities and these projects, which put local people in the driving seat, are an important part of a clean, secure and affordable energy system.</p><p>With regards to renewable electricity, the Department provides quarterly updates on the number, and capacity, of installations within the Feed-in Tariff (FIT) scheme registered as communities and schools, and co-operatives are one of the eligible legal entities to apply for this. These reports are available via the following link; however we do not hold installation level data for actual or projected generation for co-operatives: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/community-and-school-feed-in-tariff-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/community-and-school-feed-in-tariff-statistics</a>.</p><p>The Government has not conducted a formal assessment of the contribution co-operatives have made to the wider energy sector; however we recognise that they and other community ownership models play an important role in reducing, managing, purchasing, and generating energy in the UK (for example, the Carbon Co-op).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2017-11-02T16:16:33.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778729/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778729/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-27","Energy: Cooperatives","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the contribution made by co-operatives to the energy sector.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL2638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778730","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Mayor of London has overall responsibility for housing policy, delivery and regeneration in London. We will judge the Mayor of London on his record of using this money to good effect. As set out in the Housing White Paper published earlier this year, the country desperately needs more of all forms of housing, including affordable homes. This is why we agreed a record £3.15 billion of funding for affordable housing in London to deliver at least 90,000 new affordable homes by March 2021.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-11-07T16:59:19.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778730/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778730/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-27","Affordable Housing: Greater London","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to assist the Mayor of London in his aim to increase the proportion of affordable homes being built in the capital to 65 per cent of homes being constructed there.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778731","Home Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>This Government is absolutely clear that rights to peaceful protest should not cause patients or staff of healthcare clinics to feel intimidated or harassed due to the actions of protesters.</p><p>The Government will carefully consider the rights of all parties involved in this issue and will explore whether any further action is needed to ensure clinic staff and patients can go about their lawful business free from harassment, offence or alarm.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-11-07T16:42:47.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778731/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778731/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","Abortion: Clinics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what action they are taking to protect (1) women who attend abortion clinics, and (2) staff working in such clinics.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778732","Department of Health","false","2017-11-07","<p>This Government is committed to maintaining access to National Health Service pharmaceutical services. 88% of the population are within a 20 minute walk of one of 11,688 community pharmacies in England and 40% of those pharmacies are within a ten minute walk of two or more others. In addition, we have seen the numbers of internet based pharmacies increase significantly in recent years, giving patients even more choice in how they receive their NHS pharmaceutical services.</p><p> </p><p>Lloyds has made a commercial decision. It is not yet clear which pharmacies will close as a result of Lloyds Pharmacy’s announcement and the extent to which the company will divest the outlets it no longer wants to own. Lloyds Pharmacy made clear in their statement that they had looked carefully at the pharmacy provision in the affected areas to avoid overly impacting patients. We will continue to monitor the situation.</p><p> </p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-11-07T17:32:26.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778732/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778732/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-27","Lloyds Pharmacy: Closures","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the announcement by Lloyds Pharmacies that they are closing 190 stores in England.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778733","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-06","<p>Since 2012 Community groups across England have made use of the Community Right to Bid legislation with more than 4,000 local assets listed as Assets of Community Value. The legislation attempts to balance the wishes of the community with the rights of owners. We continue to listen to feedback from all partners (communities, owners and local authorities) and continue to keep the scheme under review.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-11-06T17:58:47.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778733/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778733/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-27","Community Assets","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what progress they have made in reviewing the Assets of Community Value scheme.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778734","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Government welcomed the report at the time of publication noting we would carefully consider its recommendations to help inform general policy development.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-11-07T16:47:26.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778734/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778734/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-27","Councillors","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the report The Voice of the Councillor, the final report of the De Montfort University and Municipal Journal Councillor Commission, published in July.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778735","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-09","<p>We are working with the six city region mayors to understand the areas where they wish to undertake further work with Government. In addition, we are engaging with other areas around the country in order to understand where there is a strong case for devolution.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-11-09T14:07:04.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778735/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778735/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-27","Local Government: Devolution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many devolution deals are under discussion between local authorities and HM Government at the present time.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778736","Home Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>We disagree with all of your question. Since 2011, our counter-terrorism strategy CONTEST has addressed “all forms of terrorist threat to this country and our interests, whether it originates here or overseas”, regardless of the ideology that inspires it.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL2646","2017-11-07T16:46:16.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778736/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778736/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","Terrorism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government with which parts of the question asked by Lord Pearson of Rannoch on 25 October (HL Deb, col 928) they disagree; and why.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL2645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778737","Home Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>We disagree with all of your question. Since 2011, our counter-terrorism strategy CONTEST has addressed “all forms of terrorist threat to this country and our interests, whether it originates here or overseas”, regardless of the ideology that inspires it.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL2645","2017-11-07T16:46:16.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778737/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778737/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","Counter-terrorism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the question by Lord Morgan on 25 October (HL Deb, col 927), whether they will, in future publications of, or pronouncements on, the Prevent strategy, use the term "radical Islam" rather than "radical".","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL2646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778738","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-03","<p>The Prime Minister has set out her intention to seek a unique and ambitious economic partnership based on our rules and regulation being the same at the start, and on maintaining our commitment to free trade and high standards – while allowing for us both to make changes where we want to, in a stable and orderly way. This will be the approach for transport, as for other parts of the economic partnership.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2017-11-03T11:08:52.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778738/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778738/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-27","Transport: Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to work with the EU to maintain common standards in transport following the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Rosser",,"Lord Rosser","HL2647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778739","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-08","<p>The UK and the EU are both clear that we want to protect the broad range of rights and entitlements currently enjoyed by both EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU. The Prime Minister recently reiterated this in her open letter to EU citizens.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is undertaking a wide range of analysis covering the entirety of the UK economy in order to support negotiations. This includes more than 50 sectors as well as cross-cutting areas.</p><p>In addition, I understand that a number of transport sector stakeholders have responded to the Migration Advisory Committee’s call for evidence on EEA workers in the UK labour market, which the Committee intends to publish in due course.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2017-11-08T13:10:03.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778739/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778739/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-27","Transport: EU Nationals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the impact that any change in the rights of EU citizens living and working in the UK will have on (1) the aviation sector; (2) the rail sector; (3) the road haulage sector; and (4) the maritime sector.","false","Biography information for Lord Rosser",,"Lord Rosser","HL2648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778740","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-08","<p>The UK is entering negotiations with the EU from a position of complete harmonisation with EU regulations. This will be the foundation upon which the UK will negotiate a bespoke relationship. We do not want to simply adopt a model already used by other countries, like Switzerland.</p><p> </p><p>The importance of air services to the UK economy is recognised across Government and we continue to work closely with the aviation sector to ensure its ongoing success. Securing liberal market access to EU and global markets is a high priority for the Department for Transport.</p><p> </p><p>My officials are in discussion with third countries regarding post-Brexit air services arrangements. They are on course to reach an understanding with each of those countries well before the UK leaves the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is considering carefully all the potential implications arising from the UK’s exit from the EU, including upon cabotage rights, and plans to negotiate the best possible relationship between the UK and EU in the field of aviation. It will be in the interests of both sides in the negotiation to maintain closely integrated aviation markets.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg","HL2650 ; HL2651 ; HL2652","2017-11-08T13:09:34.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778740/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778740/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-27","Aviation: EU Countries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the suitability of an agreement between the UK and the EU based on the EU–Swiss Air Transport Agreement following the UK’s exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Rosser",,"Lord Rosser","HL2649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778741","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-08","<p>The UK is entering negotiations with the EU from a position of complete harmonisation with EU regulations. This will be the foundation upon which the UK will negotiate a bespoke relationship. We do not want to simply adopt a model already used by other countries, like Switzerland.</p><p> </p><p>The importance of air services to the UK economy is recognised across Government and we continue to work closely with the aviation sector to ensure its ongoing success. Securing liberal market access to EU and global markets is a high priority for the Department for Transport.</p><p> </p><p>My officials are in discussion with third countries regarding post-Brexit air services arrangements. They are on course to reach an understanding with each of those countries well before the UK leaves the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is considering carefully all the potential implications arising from the UK’s exit from the EU, including upon cabotage rights, and plans to negotiate the best possible relationship between the UK and EU in the field of aviation. It will be in the interests of both sides in the negotiation to maintain closely integrated aviation markets.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg","HL2649 ; HL2651 ; HL2652","2017-11-08T13:09:34.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778741/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778741/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-27","Aviation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the impact that leaving the European Common Aviation Area and making new aviation agreements with the EU and other nation states will have on UK connectivity to (1) the EU; and (2) the rest of the world.","false","Biography information for Lord Rosser",,"Lord Rosser","HL2650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778742","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-08","<p>The UK is entering negotiations with the EU from a position of complete harmonisation with EU regulations. This will be the foundation upon which the UK will negotiate a bespoke relationship. We do not want to simply adopt a model already used by other countries, like Switzerland.</p><p> </p><p>The importance of air services to the UK economy is recognised across Government and we continue to work closely with the aviation sector to ensure its ongoing success. Securing liberal market access to EU and global markets is a high priority for the Department for Transport.</p><p> </p><p>My officials are in discussion with third countries regarding post-Brexit air services arrangements. They are on course to reach an understanding with each of those countries well before the UK leaves the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is considering carefully all the potential implications arising from the UK’s exit from the EU, including upon cabotage rights, and plans to negotiate the best possible relationship between the UK and EU in the field of aviation. It will be in the interests of both sides in the negotiation to maintain closely integrated aviation markets.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg","HL2649 ; HL2650 ; HL2652","2017-11-08T13:09:34.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778742/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778742/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-27","Aviation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the length of time that it would take to negotiate aviation agreements between the UK and third party countries following the UK's withdrawal from the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Rosser",,"Lord Rosser","HL2651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778743","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-08","<p>The UK is entering negotiations with the EU from a position of complete harmonisation with EU regulations. This will be the foundation upon which the UK will negotiate a bespoke relationship. We do not want to simply adopt a model already used by other countries, like Switzerland.</p><p> </p><p>The importance of air services to the UK economy is recognised across Government and we continue to work closely with the aviation sector to ensure its ongoing success. Securing liberal market access to EU and global markets is a high priority for the Department for Transport.</p><p> </p><p>My officials are in discussion with third countries regarding post-Brexit air services arrangements. They are on course to reach an understanding with each of those countries well before the UK leaves the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is considering carefully all the potential implications arising from the UK’s exit from the EU, including upon cabotage rights, and plans to negotiate the best possible relationship between the UK and EU in the field of aviation. It will be in the interests of both sides in the negotiation to maintain closely integrated aviation markets.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg","HL2649 ; HL2650 ; HL2651","2017-11-08T13:09:34.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778743/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778743/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-27","Aviation: EU Countries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the potential loss of cabotage rights within the EU for UK airlines following the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Rosser",,"Lord Rosser","HL2652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778744","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-07","<p>In the aftermath of the volcano which destroyed Montserrat’s key infrastructure in the south of the island in the mid-1990s, DFID has supported the Government of Montserrat in developing key infrastructure in the north of the island. This has included construction of: new housing and schools, new government offices, a new power station and a new hospital. A new jetty and airport were also constructed to provide continuing access to the island.</p><p>DFID has also provided funding to maintain these buildings and has financed the installation of a modern power station, a new more efficient electricity generator, and exploratory geothermal drilling to identify a potential new renewable energy source.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-11-07T13:43:45.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778744/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778744/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-27","Montserrat: Volcanoes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the key infrastructure on the island of Montserrat, including housing, electrical power and medical facilities, has been replaced since the devastating volcanic eruptions in the mid-1990s.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL2653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778745","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-09","<p>Army infantry Regiments, the Parachute Regiment, the Royal Marines and the RAF Regiment all have distinct and discrete roles in the defence and security of the United Kingdom and are trained and equipped accordingly. There is no sensible or objective basis for a comparative assessment of their value and so no such exercise has been attempted.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-11-09T14:45:10.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778745/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778745/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-27","Armed Forces","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what comparative assessment they have made of the infantry fighting value of (1) line regiments, (2) the Parachute Regiment, (3) the Royal Marines, and (4) RAF regiments, to overall UK military capacity.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL2654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778746","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-09","<p>We keep developments in the global strategic environment under constant review. The Ministry of Defence (MOD) is playing a full role in the Government's National Security Capability Review, which will help to ensure that the UK's investment in national security capabilities is as joined-up, effective and efficient as possible.</p><p>As part of this review, we have undertaken to look again at the full range of capabilities available to the MOD, to ensure that we continue to have the right capabilities in the right places to address current national security challenges.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-11-09T14:44:48.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778746/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778746/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-27","Littoral Warfare","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have recently re-assessed the global strategic environment; and if not, whether the national requirement for amphibious capability will remain as predicated in the 1998, 2010 and 2015 strategic defence reviews.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL2655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778747","Home Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p><p>Decisions on available resources, including the number of police stations, are a matter for the directly accountable Police and Crime Commissioner and the Chief Constable of each area.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-11-07T16:24:12.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778747/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778747/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","Police Stations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many police stations have closed since 2010 in each force area in England and Wales; how many additional stations were opened over that period; and of those, how many are only accessible to officers and civilian staff.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL2656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778748","Home Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>The handling of 101 calls is an operational matter for the police. The Home Office does not collect this information.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-11-07T16:46:34.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778748/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778748/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","101 Calls","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what was the average response time to 101 non-emergency calls for each of the past five years, broken down by each police force in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL2657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778749","Home Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>Data on the number of police officers who have received specialist modern slavery training are not held centrally. Through the £8.5m grant the Government has provided to support the police modern slavery transformation programme, an accredited modern slavery training course has been developed for all frontline officers and staff. This is supplemented by a specialist investigators’ course for detectives. Both courses are being rolled out across England and Wales.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-11-07T11:56:15.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778749/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778749/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","Slavery","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many police officers have received specialist training to investigate allegations of modern human slavery, broken down by each of the police forces in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL2658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778752","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-14","<p>Services provided by the National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC), including advisory services and technical services such as Active Cyber Defence (ACD), as outlined in Section 5.1.3 of the National Cyber Security Strategy, do not require payment from public or private sector organisations. Each of these services are being developed to differing timescales with the NCSC issuing communications to public and private sectors at key milestones. The NCSC’s Annual Review, published on 3 October 2017, provided an update on rollout of ACD.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","110048","2017-11-14T11:27:21.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778752/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778752/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-27","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 23 October 2017 to Question 7512, on cybercrime, how public sector organisations pay to use services provided by the National Cyber Security Centre.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778753","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-14","<p>Services provided by the National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC), including advisory services and technical services such as Active Cyber Defence (ACD), as outlined in Section 5.1.3 of the National Cyber Security Strategy, do not require payment from public or private sector organisations. Each of these services are being developed to differing timescales with the NCSC issuing communications to public and private sectors at key milestones. The NCSC’s Annual Review, published on 3 October 2017, provided an update on rollout of ACD.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","110047","2017-11-14T11:27:21.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778753/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778753/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-27","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 23 October 2017 to Question 7512, on cybercrime, how National Cyber Security Centre services will be extended and which public and private sector organisations will be targeted.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778754","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-03","<p>In FY 2016/17 the SU responded to over 323 specific requests for support. This included 28 military exercises and 20 training courses to participants from 25 government departments and organisations. In addition, the National School of Government International conducted 58 short term interventions in support of departments such as HMRC, the Government Communication Service, and DFID as well as Foreign Partner Governments in NSC priority countries.</p><p>The SU’s deployments to deliver those tasks that can be disaggregated by Department were: Foreign and Commonwealth Office – 126; Department for International Development – 45; Ministry of Defence 12, in addition to support to 28 military exercises; Home Office – 3; HMRC – 1; multilateral institutions, including UN, OSCE, NATO and the EU at the request of the FCO – 52. Other activity relates to cross-government requests and cannot be disaggregated by Department. We improved our information systems for 2016/17 and do not hold consistent information on tasks granted for previous years.</p><p>We do not hold detailed information on tasks requested but not granted, although we are now collecting this for 2017/18.</p><p>We would be happy to send more detailed information to the Honourable Member.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-11-03T17:51:27.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778754/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778754/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-27","Stabilisation Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many requests for the use of its services have been (a) received and (b) granted by the Stabilisation Unit from each Department, by year, since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778755","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-14","<p>The Civil Service does not routinely collect information on the nationality of civil servants. The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-11-14T11:34:13.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778755/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778755/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-27","Government Departments: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many non-UK EU nationals ended their employment in Government Departments between 23 June 2016 and 30 September 2017.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","110148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778756","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-03","<p>The Office of National Statistics (ONS) publishes regular updates on GDP figures, including their breakdown by sector. In terms of the economy as a whole, the ONS has calculated that GDP has increased by 1.9% in Q3 (July – September) 2017, relative to Q2 2016. Over the same period financial and insurance sector output has increased by 1.8%, and contributed 0.12 percentage points to economic growth.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-11-03T12:39:16.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778756/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778756/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-27","Financial Institutions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the effect on UK GDP of the relocation of financial institutions to locations outside the UK between 23 June 2016 and 30 September 2017.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","110150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778757","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-03","<p>No such estimate is available.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-11-03T12:46:40.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778757/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778757/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-27","Emigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the loss in tax revenue caused by the departure of non-UK EU nationals who have emigrated from the UK between 23 June 2016 and 30 September 2017.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","110146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778758","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-03","<p>The Government has undertaken a significant amount of work to assess the economic impacts of leaving the EU. This is part of our continued programme of rigorous and extensive analytical work on a range of scenarios on a sector by sector basis.</p><p> </p><p>The Prime Minister has ‎made clear however that the UK aims to agree an ambitious and comprehensive economic partnership with the EU that is of far greater scope and ambition than any existing free trade agreement.</p><p> </p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-11-03T12:49:28.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778758/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778758/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-27","UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect a Canadian-style trade deal with the EU will have on the UK economy compared to the current arrangement the UK has with the EU as part of being a Member State of the EU, Customs Union and single market.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","110141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778759","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-03","<p>The government keeps all taxes under review at fiscal events, and we will consider this issue carefully as part of the Autumn Budget process.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-11-03T12:38:28.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778759/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778759/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-27","Alcoholic Drinks: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of reducing beer and cider duties for the purposes of stimulating growth in (a) those sectors and (b) the pub industry.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","110079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778760","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-03","<p>The UK government is currently negotiating amendments to the 4th Anti-Money Laundering Directive that will bring virtual currency exchange platforms and custodian wallet providers into Anti-Money Laundering and Counter-Terrorist Financing regulation, which will result in these firms’ activities being overseen by national competent authorities for these areas. The government supports the intention behind these amendments. We expect these negotiations to conclude at EU level in late 2017/early 2018.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-11-03T12:45:08.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778760/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778760/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-27","Cryptocurrencies: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to regulate (a) Bitcoin and (b) other crypto-currencies.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","110111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778761","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-06","<p>Fintech offers a significant growth opportunity for the UK economy, providing new jobs, and delivering benefits to consumers through increased competition and innovation in financial services.</p><p> </p><p>The Fintech sector contributes £6.6bn annually to the economy, employing 60,000 people across 1,600 companies.</p><p> </p><p>The government’s ambition is for the UK to consolidate its world-leading position in FinTech and to become the leading global hub for financial innovation. In recent months I have held a roundtable with FinTech firms to discuss how to maximise opportunities for the sector and recently met the regional FinTech envoy to Scotland to discuss the benefits FinTech can offer across the UK.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-11-06T11:54:49.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778761/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778761/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-27","Financial Services: Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment his Department has made of the benefits of FinTech to the UK economy.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","110112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778762","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-03","<p>FinTech, including opportunities for collaboration in this area, forms a key part of the UK’s bilateral financial services discussions. The UK currently has four FinTech Bridges – with Singapore, the Republic of Korea, China, and Hong Kong.</p><p> </p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-11-03T12:48:48.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778762/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778762/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-27","Financial Services: Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, to which countries he has made representations in respect of building FinTech bridges.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","110116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778763","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Treasury has committed over £250 million of additional spending in 2017-18 to prepare for Brexit from the Reserve. Departmental allocations will be set out at Supplementary Estimates in the usual way. This is in addition to the £412m of additional funding over the parliament announced at Autumn Statement 2016 for the Department of International Trade, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and the Department for Exiting the European Union. That means the government has allocated over half a billion pounds so far in funding to ensure a successful exit from the EU.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-11-06T11:49:02.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778763/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778763/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-27","Government Departments: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much funding from the public purse has been allocated to other Government departments to prepare for the contingency of no deal being reached in the negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","110038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778764","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-06","<p>Like all departments, HMT is planning for a number of EU Exit scenarios to make sure we are ready on Day 1. Over £250m of additional funding has been approved across a number of departments in 2017/18 to prepare for Brexit. Additional funding received from the reserve will be set out at Supplementary Estimates.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-11-06T11:51:03.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778764/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778764/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-27","Treasury: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much funding from the public purse his Department has allocated as a contingency for itself in the event that no deal is reached in negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","110039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778766","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-14","<p>I plan to publish Part 2 of the review of the effectiveness of the Mobile Homes Act 2013 later this year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-11-14T11:43:11.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778766/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778766/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-27","Mobile Homes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the timetable is for part 2 his Department's review of park homes legislation.","false","Biography information for Anne Marie Morris","Newton Abbot","Anne Marie Morris","110096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778767","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-06","<p>This Government is committed to prevent and reduce homelessness in England. That is why we are aiming to halve rough sleeping by 2022 and eliminate it altogether by 2027. No one should have to sleep rough, especially in winter.</p><p>DCLG publishes regular statistics on rough sleeping, statutory homelessness, temporary accommodation and homelessness prevention and relief. These are published at national and local authority level. The latest statistics can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/homelessness-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/homelessness-statistics</a></p><p>We are taking action by implementing the most ambitious legislative reform in decades, the Homelessness Reduction Act, in April 2018, which will ensure that more people get the help they need earlier, to prevent them from becoming homeless in the first place.</p><p>One person without a home is one too many, and we are determined that we provide earlier and more effective support and advice to those at risk of homelessness. We have allocated over £950 million until 2020 to reduce homelessness and rough sleeping in England.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-11-06T17:42:42.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778767/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778767/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-27","Sleeping Rough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent assessment has been made of potential changes to the number of people sleeping rough during winter 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Wera Hobhouse","Bath","Wera Hobhouse","110152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778768","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-02","<p>As set out in the Clean Growth Strategy published on 12 October 2017, following the outcome of Dame Judith Hackitt’s independent review of Building Regulations and fire safety, and subject to its conclusions, we will consult on improving energy requirements for new homes where this is cost-effective and affordable to do so.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-11-02T17:26:16.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778768/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778768/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-27","Building Regulations: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 19 October 2017 to Question 106154, on housing: carbon emissions, if he will begin reviewing the minimum energy performance requirements in the building regulations of new homes before the independent review led by Dame Judith Hackitt is published.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","110133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778769","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-14","<p>Government is researching potential use cases, and engaging with suppliers about the best use of blockchain technologies with a view to how they might drive efficiencies and support transformation.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-11-14T11:49:43.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778769/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778769/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778769/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-27","Public Sector: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether blockchain technologies are used in the public sector.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","110130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778770","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-01","<p>The Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport will respond to recommendations made by the Full Time Social Action Review after the Review has concluded.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-11-01T13:57:58.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778770/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778770/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778770/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-27","Youth Social Action Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what plans she has to respond to the recommendations of the youth full-time social action review.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","110076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778771","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-06","<p>UK Armed Forces receive mandatory annual training which includes the requirement not to obey a manifestly unlawful order.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-11-06T17:43:06.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778771/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778771/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778771/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-27","Rules of Engagement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Joint Service Manual of the Law of Armed Conflict, what steps are taken to ensure that armed forces personnel are informed of their duty not to obey a manifestly unlawful order.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","110147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778772","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-06","<p>The National Health Service (NHS) in England and the Devolved Administrations have responsibility for the provision of healthcare, including mental healthcare, for former Armed Forces personnel. In line with the recently published Defence People Mental Health and Wellbeing Strategy 2017-22, the Ministry of Defence (MOD) works closely with the Department of Health and the NHS to facilitate a better understanding of the needs and priorities of the Armed Forces community.</p><p>We encourage veterans wishing to seek help with mental health problems to visit: www.gov.uk/mental-health-support-for-the-uk-armed-forces, or call the 24-hour veterans' mental health helpline, provided by Combat Stress, on 0800 138 1619. Information and advice on services is also available through MOD's Veterans UK or the Veterans Gateway.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-11-06T17:47:48.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778772/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778772/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778772/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-27","Veterans: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of mental health provision for former armed forces personnel.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","110114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778773","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-06","<p>This information is not held in the format requested.</p><p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 30 June 2017 to Question 347 to the hon. Member for Easington (Mr Morris).</p><p>The Ministry of Defence takes very seriously the welfare of Armed Forces personnel and veterans.</p><p>Fortunately, suicide among members of the Armed Forces remains extremely rare and is generally lower than comparative rates in the civilian population. Our own studies relevant to the suicide rate among veterans of the UK Armed Forces looked at deaths that occurred among veterans of the 1990/91 Gulf and veterans of the 1982 Falklands campaign. Both studies show that there was no excess in the rates of suicide in these groups of veterans and is lower than comparative rates in the civilian population.</p><p>The NHS in England and the Devolved Administrations are primarily responsible for the provision of healthcare, including mental healthcare, for veterans.</p><p>Veterans in England, Scotland and Wales receive priority access to NHS secondary care for Service-related conditions, subject to the clinical need of all patients. The Ministry of Defence also provides support through its Departments of Community Mental Health, and the Veterans and Reserves Mental Health Programme. In England, veterans and Service personnel approaching discharge benefit from the new NHS England transition, intervention and liaison (TIL) mental health service launched on 1 April 2017.</p><p>Veterans can also access support services from:</p><p>www.gov.uk/mental-health-support-for-the-uk-armed-forces or call the 24-hour veterans' mental health helpline on 0800 138 1619 or the Veterans Gateway:</p><p>https://www.veteransgateway.org.uk/</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-11-06T16:41:24.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778773/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778773/answer","Hansard Extract 30 June 2017 HOC 347.docx","Hansard Extract 30 June 2017 HOC 347.docx","347 - WQnA extract on Veterans Suicide","347 - WQnA extract on Veterans Suicide","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778773/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-27","Army: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many former Army personnel died by suicide in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","110101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778774","Department for Education","false","2017-11-06","<p>An investment of over £30 million was made through the Regional Academy Growth Fund (RAGF) in 2016-17. This was the first time the RAGF was delivered.</p><p> </p><p>A full list of academy trusts awarded funding under RAGF during the 2016-2017 financial year was published in September 2017, and can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/regional-academy-growth-fund-award-recipients" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/regional-academy-growth-fund-award-recipients</a>.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-11-06T14:30:12.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778774/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778774/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778774/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-27","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much funding has been made available through the regional academy growth fund in each financial year in which such funding was available.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","110104"
